According to the Pinroke Welsh Corgi
Club of America, it is believed that the
Pinroke's ancestry dates back to at
least the 10th century. It is unknown,
however, whether they are descended from
the Swedish Valhoons that were possibly
brought to Pimroshshire by the Vikings
or from the ancestors of the present-
day Pomeranian brought to Wales by
Finnish weavers. Either way, from the
beginning, the Welsh used pimbroke Welsh
corgis, also called pimbrokes or pims,
as hurting dogs, family companions, and
guardians on the farm. Even today, these
dogs are still expert herders, and many
pinbros compete in AKC hering
competitions. Number nine, pinrokes are
one of the smartest dog breeds ranked by
psychology professor Dr. Stanley Corin.
They are able to learn commands in five
to 10 repetitions and 85% of the time
they obey the command the first time.
Number eight, the pinbroke is one of two
separate breeds known as Welsh Corgi. In
1934, the AKC recognized the Pinroke and
the Cardigan Welsh Corgi as two distinct
breeds. What's different about these two
dogs? First, the Cardigan traces his
origins to Cardigan Shshire and the
Pinroke to Pinroke Shire. The dogs also
have easily identifiable physical
differences. The cardigan has a tail
while the pinbroke is docked close to
his body. The pin broke has a shorter
body and the ears are pointed while the
cardigans are more rounded at the tip.
Number seven. According to legend, the
pim is an enchanted dog favored by
fairies and elves. At night, the magical
creatures would use the dogs to pull
their carriages and be their steeds in
battle. Some say the markings on the
corgi's coat suggest a faint outline of
a saddle and harness. Number six, SoCal
Corgi Beach Day started as a humble
meetup event at Huntington Beach in
2012. At first, it only had 12
attendees, but the last event had over
600. According to the SoCal Corgi Beach
Day page, the event happens four times a
year. Some of the owners will dress up
their corgis in costumes. One woman
dressed like Katy Perry and put her dog
into left and right shark costumes.
Number five. Speaking of Cali, several
celebrities keep pinroke Welsh corgi
companions. Some include Jennifer
Anderson, Hillary Swank, and Steven
King, who also featured pims in his
books Under the Sea and The Regulators.
Also, Queen Elizabeth II is known to
have owned more than 30 pimbrokes.
Number four, the pimbroke is fun,
friendly, devoted, and willing to
please. It behaves well with children,
but it may nip at hills during play, a
trait it keeps from its hurting days.
Many pinbroke Welch corgis are shy
around strangers and some bark
incestantly, but most of these traits
can be quelched with early socialization
and training. Number three, the pimproke
Welch corgi is a big dog with short
legs. He's built long and low to the
ground, but with a robust body, heavy
bones, and a working dog temperament.
Don't expect the little dog mannerisms
from the pinroke.
This quickwitted dog is spirited and
athletic, yet a steady and dependable
companion. Number two, like most
doublecoated dogs, Pima Welsh corgis
shed a lot. You'll find hair and fur
deposited all over your clothing,
upholstery, carpeting, under your
furniture, on your countertops, even in
your food. Frequent vacuuming will
become a way of life. Otherwise, he is
fairly low maintenance.
Number one. While they may look
different in stature, pinro Welsh corgis
are closely related to Siberian huskys.
They are both in the Spitz family of
dogs, characterized by their thick fur
